value.value: Posteriormost longitudinal vein (Stark et al., 1999; Blair, 2007; Alba et al., 2021). It branches from wing vein L5 (Sturtevant and Bier, 1995; Alba et al., 2021) and comprises the second anterior cubital vein and the product of its fusion with the first anal vein (McAlpine, 1981; Stark et al., 1999; Blair, 2007). It is relatively short and does not reach the wing margin (Ferris, 1950; Stark et al., 1999; Blair, 2007).

A short wing vein that runs anterior-posterior, joining two longitudinal wing veins (Stark et al., 1999). It lacks underlying tracheae and its formation requires a different set of genes to longitudinal veins (Stark et al., 1999).
Crossvein that connects the proximal anterior wing margin (proximal costal vein) and the subcostal vein (Ferris, 1950; Fabian et al., 2016).
Crossvein that connects the wing vein L3 and wing vein L4.
Crossvein that connects the wing vein L4 and wing vein L5.
A region of wing cuticle interposed between wing veins.
Anterior/proximal wing cell (intervein) region bounded by wing vein L1 posteriorly, the costal vein anteriorly and the humeral crossvein proximally.

value.value: Paired dorsal 'appendage' of the adult mesothoracic segment. It is a freely movable, capitate stalk. It develops from the dorsal mesothoracic disc. It is used for flight balance.

definition.value: Exists only in females, it has lost its sclerotization in males. In the latter, the spiracle associated with this segment is located more anteriorly, close to tergite 6 (Ferris, 1950). May be some controversy on segment assignment.

definition.value: It is considered that the sternite of abdominal segment 11, in both males and females, is membranous (Ferris, 1950).

value.value: A chordotonal organ associated with the anterior of abdominal sternite 2. It is visible externally as a raised patch of smooth cuticle without trichomes or bristles. It consists of two clusters of scolopidia (FBbt:00005217), one on either side of the ventral midline (Smith and Shepherd, 1996). The sensory neurons of Wheeler's organ project through the second segmental nerve of the abdomen and then through the abdominal neuromeres via dorso-lateral tract of the ventral fasciculus (DLV), to terminate in the prothoracic neuromere (Smith and Shepherd, 1996).

A spiracle of the adult abdomen. There are 7 pairs of these, in segments A1-7, in the anterior region of the pleural membrane. Each has a rigid circular rim and the opening leads to a tubular atrium lined by inward projecting circular lamellae. Where the atrium joins the trachea, the passage is constricted by a deep fold in the anterior wall which can be closed by the action of an associated spiracular occlusor muscle (FBbt:00013334).
Any adult spiracle (FBbt:00003120) that is part of some abdominal segment 3 (FBbt:00000024).
Any adult spiracle (FBbt:00003120) that is part of some abdominal segment 4 (FBbt:00000025).
Any adult spiracle (FBbt:00003120) that is part of some abdominal segment 5 (FBbt:00000026).
Any adult spiracle (FBbt:00003120) that is part of some abdominal segment 6 (FBbt:00000027).
Most posterior of the adult abdominal spiracles. It is located lateral to the posterior of tergite 6.

Membrane that is found laterally, between the tergites, on the dorsal side, and the sternites on the ventral side of the adult external abdomen. The abdominal spiracles are found on the most anterior region of the pleural membrane.

The set of external structures of adult abdominal segment 10 that makes up the anal apparatus (Rice et al., 2019; McQueen et al., 2022). It develops from the anal primordium of the genital disc (Casares et al., 1997; Keisman et al., 2001).
Set of female external structures, originating from segment 10, that makes up the anal apparatus (McQueen et al., 2022). It develops from the female genital disc (McQueen et al., 2022).
